<br>
I'm not entirely sure if this is fact or just a really pervasive myth.  I do know that occasionally I've been in raids where a gating/CHing/summoning mob would be purposefully provoked into nuking or AEing in the belief that it would expend it's CH mana, and thus avoid too messy of a wipe if it got off a gate and started summoning.  It seemed to work, as the mob really didn't cast anything other than a few gate attempts once it fired off so many nukes.<br>
<br>
One thing that I have noticed is that if I get a mob to cast on me repeatedly, as a 61 wizard with my resists this tends to be a pretty safe proposition from my end, it will eventually give up and start charging me.  Occasionally, mobs I've rooted will stop casting for no apparent reason, I guess because I've run them dry.  I'm not sure if that's a sign the mob has a finite pool, or if it just means that the coding contains an argument of &quot;if X-Y spells are resisted, then melee&quot;, with no conditions to deal with roots or snares.  I've only tested it with any regularity on SD sun reavers and CS sirens, I guess I'd have to start quadding around more casters to do a more reliable check.<br>
<br>
Zerlatik Flaimweaver<br>
Sorcerer of Tholuxe Paells<br>
